Barack Obama will be the fourth American President to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, to spend 26 hours there and be the fourth American President in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
Among other things, the $1.4 million diploma, medal and cheque will be handed over to him for his outstanding efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and will have a busy program.
He will first go to the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the very first time the five members of the Committee who chose him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple's planning then includes an interview with the King of Norway Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will meet its summit in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive it, but only the third to be awarded the prize in the Committee itself.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan when the prize was given.
The president does not want to avoid this because he is aware that he receives this prize by being a president who leads a war in two countries at the moment.
He reinforced the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to emphasize.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check of ten million Swedish kroner (about 1.1 million Euros).
He intends to donate it to charitable works, but he has not yet decided in concrete terms which ones.
His busy program will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant at that price at first.
He mentioned, for example, the feeling that he did not deserve it fully.
He also repeated several times that it is not a price for himself alone, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
From the announcement, he stated that it would be an "invitation to act" for him.
