United States: Repetition Is Mother of Wisdom
It even becomes comical, the diligent effort with which Barack Obama, president of the reputation of the wise, replicates his predecessor's strategy on the Afghan issue, which he considered to be very simple.
When he ended up letting his doctrine sweat so eagerly awaited, it turned out that he had copied it to carbon paper since Bush's Iraqi scenario three years ago.
Not content to use in the text itself several times the expression "as in Iraq", he did not hesitate, which is more, to use the title of the Bush speech of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward"
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush's idea of sending new reinforcements to a civil war-burned Iraq as "irresponsibility and a catastrophic decision in its consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of the campaign commanders, was the only possible and likely to succeed to such an extent that the newspapers currently do not speak at all of Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, that said, objectively speaking, he left his successor a much more favourable final situation than one could hope.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who called for an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the White House's reluctance despite the habit of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favourable.
The president hesitated for three months, but in the absence of a better option, at least he scammed the general of 10,000 soldiers.
It has succeeded in removing the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though it originally had 10,000.
What brings the most problems in Obama's entire strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete this whole process within three years. Obama's entire doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that half an increase will bring the same fruits as the increase in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honour the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out by the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
Under these circumstances, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, who are accustomed to changing their day-to-day leadership according to their arrangement.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will only remain dust in the eyes behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is uniquely complex to balance the interests of various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity about the reports, which are still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "prompt state to act", which is the basic purpose of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The temporal horizon of Obama's strategy is perplexed by its voluntarism.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic heart and out of reality can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their "quick return home" will bring a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will regard it as the indirect admission of the American defeat.
The latest NATO summit has shown that the Europeans' willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is moving towards the negative.
European policies do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the mountains of Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the enhanced sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves faced with the very difficult question of solving the problem through the use of military force.
For example, we will have to respond when, according to Obama, America comes to the victorious withdrawal of Afghan troops.
Each such solution will, however, lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only trick for Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential elections and therefore there is still enough time for him to plan on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
