Czech discovery: a substance that works on "endurant" HIV viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists test new combinations that can slow the spread of HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality takes, in some cases, the top on the fact that the combination does not deal as intensively with the common variants of the virus as well as some medicines already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at this time.
However, the life of patients can be radically prolonged through a mixture of drugs that prevent the spread of HIV virus in the body.
Their consumption, however, results in a series of side effects.
Moreover, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what is called resistant viruses on which drugs no longer have effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarboranes are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of the researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of molecular mechanics of their links to the proteins of the virus.
Metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two cages with multiple walls are formed by boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
A traitoric and resistant virus.
