The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If vaccination has started last year or earlier, the following vaccinations will have to be paid for themselves.
The first dose of vaccine should be administered between the child's 3rd and 5th months.
Last year already, one quarter of families voluntarily vaccinated their children against pneumococcals.
Yet the parents paid 1600 crowns or more for a dose.
Immunization of the youngest requires four doses.
The specialists estimate that every year health insurance spends 300 to 450,000 kroner in doses of vaccine.
However, they save on the medical care that non-vaccinated children would require.
To date, the State has spent approximately 500 000 kroner per year on all vaccinations of children.
The refunded vaccination was introduced with the "Janota package".
Pneumococcals are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections such as meninges inflammation and blood poisoning.
According to hospital investigations, there are up to 28 deaths of children under 10 years of age due to pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced the refunded vaccination.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
There are opinions on a possible vaccination obligation in the future.
From January, it must be settled by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský said that mandatory vaccination would be more positive.
Its association has long promoted vaccination against pneumococcals.
At an international conference in which our association participated, the specialists were not really satisfied with the fact that we have an optional vaccination.
It's not ideal.
On the other hand, we are happy to have at least been able to impose this.
I think it is a direction that must now be followed, said Kalovský.
But the Ministry of Health does not want to change the process of vaccination against pneumococcals.
We absolutely do not envisage it at the moment, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeń.
Optional vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Specialized Society of Paediatrics, acknowledges that a vaccination based on volunteerata its defects.
If all children were vaccinated, a decrease in vaccination renewals could be considered "In the situation where the vaccine costs such a sum I understand the decision making vaccination optional," says Cabrnochová.
The specialists predict that as early as next year, more than 80 percent of new parents will have their infants vaccinated.
Vaccination against pneumococcals also breaks because it is the first vaccination of children that is financed by insurance and not by the State.
Cabrnochová explains that insurance should release funds for prevention, thus saving on possible future medical care.
