Managerial revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile.
For more than ten years, the attitude of the management of large enterprises towards its employees has been reminiscent of the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers prior to the marketing revolution: it is a question of making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it used to be, of imposing on consumers products designed by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering markets in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products from customer preference factors comes back regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to lethal demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the part of a much more general phenomenon that affects managers in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the enterprise, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would involve putting employees at the centre of the company's concerns in the same way as the customer.
The all-relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – encourage this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all, because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally happens, after many turns, to do what it has always done.
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As a result of major engineering schools, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old Behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the U.S. "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without them, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leviers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr comforts the leaders in a position of mechanistic governance, inadequate to today's world.
Identifying and Measuring Engagement Factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of incorporating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of realizing part of their dreams, ambitions, and projects.
Currently, only studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and return their human resources management "to the place".
They thus create a ground for the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
