Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and phenomena of illusory images for ten years: last year he published his results in a book entitled "The Unreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychosis but also of an impressive number of many other pathologies.
Among them are mental disorders such as borderline or depression, but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease, or head trauma.
It is surprising that under certain conditions even the brain of healthy people is subject to hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that treat sensory perceptions, are hyperactive or not sufficiently refrigerated; when our brain warms up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain injury or psychosis.
