75% of working mothers had professional problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is reflected in the study "Women's fertility and career in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers saw their career limited due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether the woman works or not, and the type of employment occupied.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or work poorly, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, push back the entry into life as a couple and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with fixed work have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after they have settled in a couple. This figure increases to 4.1 in those working in the public sector."These data show that women with stable employment have needed more time in their lives to obtain it, which has led them to push back the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment widely influenced maternity, but less the date of the beginning of common life," says CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those who studied elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average.
"Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education get married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
