The sale of light commercial vehicles is progressing
After almost two years, the light commercial vehicle market begins to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in Spain in November represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, they represent the first increase after 22 consecutive months of decrease, according to the figures of the employers' union of the manufacturers Anfac and Ganvam, that of the dealers.
However, the good news should be nuanced, since the comparison reference in November 2008 was particularly bad, with a decrease of 60% compared to the previous year.
Consequently, despite the rebound of last month, registrations accumulated during these 11 months are 40% below those of the previous fiscal year.
Since January, if all vehicles that fall into the category of light commercial vehicles (derived from passenger cars, pick-ups, vans, light vans and light chassis trucks) have been added, 95,853 have been sold.
Large clouds that affect their demand the most have not dissipated. Indeed, although they are also purchased by individuals, most purchases are made by small or medium-sized enterprises, which pay in almost 100% of the cases through external financing.
Thus, in addition to the restrictions involved in limiting bank loans, other factors such as the increase in unemployment or the persistence of poor economic conditions must be added.
In the face of this situation and the difference between passenger vehicles, the 2000E purchase aid has been little used.
