Emergency braking aid is now mandatory
As with the ABS brake locking system and as with the ESP stability control, emergency braking systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of shortage has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, even though, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many back shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the brake pressure in the event of an emergency detected by the system by the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always maintain the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the manufacturer of Bosch car components, one third of the drivers involved in an accident could not press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not taken full advantage of its force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, revanced, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance that the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularisation of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four casualties would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to radar or camera, detects obstacles and prevents the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps him by increasing pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes in order to minimize damage.
